WEBVTT

00:15.981 --> 00:18.639
Narrator:
Previously on "Mountain Men"...

00:18.673 --> 00:22.574
In the final days of winter,
new threats emerge.

00:22.608 --> 00:24.541
Here's fresh grizzly tracks.

00:24.576 --> 00:26.095
Boom. Boom.
Boom.

00:26.129 --> 00:27.130
[ Barking ]

00:27.165 --> 00:29.891
There's a lion in there,
that's for sure.

00:29.926 --> 00:32.584
Narrator: Disaster strikes.

00:32.618 --> 00:35.035
-[Bleep]
-Oh, my gosh.

00:35.069 --> 00:38.245
Preston: I think your truck
is done for, Eustace.

00:38.279 --> 00:39.729
Narrator:
And it's win or lose...

00:39.763 --> 00:41.524
Man: In goat hunting,
that's always the challenge

00:41.558 --> 00:44.285
is just seeing if you can
get to where they're at.

00:44.320 --> 00:47.702
That'll live to fight
another day, I guess.

00:47.737 --> 00:50.257
Narrator: ...in the never-ending
battle with the wild.

00:52.638 --> 00:56.573
Tom: Oh, boy.
Here we go.

00:56.608 --> 01:00.094
If I don't make a real good
head shot, we're in trouble.

01:00.129 --> 01:08.861
♪

01:08.896 --> 01:13.107
♪

01:13.142 --> 01:15.696
♪

01:15.730 --> 01:18.699
--Captions by VITAC--
www.vitac.com

01:18.733 --> 01:28.812
CLOSED CAPTIONING FUNDED BY
A&E TELEVISION NETWORKS

01:28.847 --> 01:30.918
Narrator: The end of winter
is a time of opportunity

01:30.952 --> 01:34.784
across the American wilderness.

01:34.818 --> 01:37.994
On the prairies
of Eastern Montana,

01:38.028 --> 01:40.721
Tom Oar is making the most
of his,

01:40.755 --> 01:43.517
looking to cap off his first
successful season in years

01:43.551 --> 01:46.071
with one last bounty
of winter meat.

01:48.280 --> 01:49.661
Here he comes.

01:49.695 --> 01:51.766
Here he comes for us.
[Bleep]

01:51.801 --> 01:54.286
There you go.

01:56.116 --> 01:57.945
[ Gunshot ]

01:57.979 --> 01:59.705
Nice shot, Tom.
Good shot.

02:04.158 --> 02:05.746
I think he's done.

02:05.780 --> 02:07.886
He looks done,
doesn't he?

02:07.920 --> 02:10.268
Nice, clean kill.
Good shot.

02:10.302 --> 02:12.891
Here comes those other guys.

02:12.925 --> 02:14.064
We should maybe
back out of here.

02:14.099 --> 02:16.584
Let's back out here.

02:21.624 --> 02:25.904
Oh, whoa.
What are they doing?

02:25.938 --> 02:29.390
That was a dominance
move there, wasn't it?

02:29.425 --> 02:30.805
Yeah.

02:30.840 --> 02:32.082
Tom: This, right now,

02:32.117 --> 02:33.808
is probably the most dangerous
part of the hunt.

02:36.501 --> 02:40.229
I'm not sure how safe Sean and I
are just standing out here

02:40.263 --> 02:42.748
in the middle of the prairie.

02:42.783 --> 02:44.681
I mean, there's no way
to outrun them.

02:44.716 --> 02:47.097
There ain't nowhere to go.

02:47.132 --> 02:50.756
Narrator: Bison are the largest
herd animal in North America.

02:50.791 --> 02:52.620
When provoked, they can charge

02:52.655 --> 02:55.071
at speeds of up
to 40 miles per hour.

02:57.384 --> 02:59.558
Sean: Easy now.
Easy now.

03:01.767 --> 03:03.217
Getting a little agitated.
Yeah.

03:03.252 --> 03:05.806
We'll just give him
some space.

03:05.840 --> 03:08.981
They're all standing
their ground.

03:09.016 --> 03:10.397
Sean: These are
these tense moments

03:10.431 --> 03:12.364
where you have to, kind of,
wait and just make sure

03:12.399 --> 03:14.539
that these other animals
don't become a threat to you

03:14.573 --> 03:17.231
because it can happen
very quickly.

03:17.266 --> 03:19.440
Narrator:
Late-winter temperatures

03:19.475 --> 03:21.649
are in the 40s
and rising quickly.

03:21.684 --> 03:24.997
In these conditions, Tom and
Sean only have a 3-hour window

03:25.032 --> 03:29.347
to skin and dress the carcass
before the meat begins to spoil.

03:29.381 --> 03:33.247
We've got 1,200 pounds of meat
that's laying right out there

03:33.282 --> 03:34.869
in the middle of the prairie.

03:34.904 --> 03:38.321
I'm not sure what we're going
to do to get to that carcass.

03:38.356 --> 03:41.255
We're just going to have to
stand here and see what happens.

03:41.290 --> 03:49.159
♪♪

03:49.194 --> 03:56.166
♪♪

03:56.201 --> 03:57.582
Narrator: Across the country

03:57.616 --> 03:59.653
in the Blue Ridge Mountain
wilderness,

04:02.690 --> 04:06.107
seven months after a devastating
tornado hit Turtle Island,

04:06.142 --> 04:09.283
the long dig-out
is nearly complete...

04:09.318 --> 04:11.975
We've had to spend
all summer, all fall,

04:12.010 --> 04:14.495
all winter just to clean up.

04:14.530 --> 04:16.670
This has been a lot of work,

04:16.704 --> 04:19.259
but we've really made
a lot of progress

04:19.293 --> 04:23.504
in spite of all the challenge
of this big storm.

04:23.539 --> 04:26.956
Narrator:
...but there's one final
clean-up job yet to be done.

04:26.990 --> 04:30.787
Clearing the dead wood that
the storm left behind.

04:30.822 --> 04:32.927
Littering the ground
like kindling,

04:32.962 --> 04:37.242
the perfect conditions
for igniting a forest fire.

04:37.277 --> 04:40.383
Eustace: Basically, we're going
to get rid of the debris

04:40.418 --> 04:42.212
by purposefully burning it

04:42.247 --> 04:46.320
instead of just having that
sitting like a time bomb

04:46.355 --> 04:47.942
just ticking.

04:47.977 --> 04:50.151
Narrator: Eustace and Preston
aim to eliminate the risk

04:50.186 --> 04:51.946
by lighting a controlled burn

04:51.981 --> 04:56.123
using a precision-fire tool
known as a drip torch.

04:56.157 --> 04:58.919
Yeah.
That ought to do about right.

04:58.953 --> 05:01.335
Well, a drip torch is just
a real simple device.

05:01.370 --> 05:04.752
It's a container that holds
a flammable fluid.

05:04.787 --> 05:06.340
And it has a pipe that runs out,

05:06.375 --> 05:08.687
allows that fluid to drip
down on the ground

05:08.722 --> 05:10.586
and set stuff on fire.

05:10.620 --> 05:12.864
Preston: Yeah.
We'll make a nozzle

05:12.898 --> 05:15.142
out of that part
right there, huh?

05:15.176 --> 05:17.903
Now I think we're
cooking with gas.

05:17.938 --> 05:21.700
My biggest fear about this fire
is having it get out of control

05:21.735 --> 05:25.463
and just burn down my entire
home and entire forest.

05:25.497 --> 05:27.603
And so what we'll do
is have that fuel

05:27.637 --> 05:31.434
come out of the spout
at a controlled rate

05:31.469 --> 05:32.953
and a controlled placement,

05:32.987 --> 05:35.576
and that's what the drip
torch is all about.

05:35.611 --> 05:38.717
So this fuel mixture is three
parts diesel fuel

05:38.752 --> 05:40.788
and one part gas.

05:40.823 --> 05:43.550
Eustace: Diesel is basically
a light oil.

05:43.584 --> 05:46.518
You want that oil to soak
into the forest floor

05:46.553 --> 05:48.693
and stay there for a while.

05:48.727 --> 05:52.421
Narrator: Diesel fuel is slow
to ignite and long-burning.

05:52.455 --> 05:54.871
Adding it to the mixture
helps to keep the explosive

05:54.906 --> 05:58.323
properties of gasoline
under control.

05:58.358 --> 06:01.084
Eustace: If you use even a
little bit too much gas here,

06:01.119 --> 06:04.260
it can be a bomb and be
dangerous and burn you up.

06:04.294 --> 06:07.194
It happens so fast,
it's just uncontrollable.

06:07.228 --> 06:09.092
You're not going to mistake
this for a bottle of wine

06:09.127 --> 06:11.888
one night, are you?

06:11.923 --> 06:14.995
That'd be a rough night
right there.

06:15.029 --> 06:17.515
Let see how it'll work.

06:20.690 --> 06:23.210
Get back.

06:26.144 --> 06:28.905
Oh, yeah.

06:28.940 --> 06:30.597
Yes, sir.

06:30.631 --> 06:34.670
We've got just the right amount
of flow of our mixture,

06:34.704 --> 06:38.605
and also it's sticking
and burning for a while.

06:38.639 --> 06:40.020
Well, it looks like
it works.

06:40.054 --> 06:41.573
Yeah.

06:41.608 --> 06:43.851
Preston: Now that we've got
that drip torch complete,

06:43.886 --> 06:45.819
it's time to go down
and start this fire.

06:45.853 --> 06:47.407
We're in the business.
-Yeah.

06:47.441 --> 06:50.271
-So let's go burn something.
-Okay.

06:50.306 --> 06:58.348
♪♪

06:58.383 --> 07:00.523
[ Wind howling ]

07:04.044 --> 07:05.735
Narrator:
In Two Rivers, Alaska...

07:05.770 --> 07:08.566
[ Howling ]

07:08.600 --> 07:10.430
...winter is in retreat,

07:10.464 --> 07:13.847
and the snow pack
is nearly gone.

07:13.881 --> 07:15.089
The change in weather signals

07:15.124 --> 07:16.677
the end of the worst
trapping season

07:16.712 --> 07:20.232
Marty Meierotto's
endured in a decade.

07:20.267 --> 07:24.374
Now, for better or worse,
it's time to cash out.

07:24.409 --> 07:26.860
Marty: Trapping season
is pretty much over.

07:26.894 --> 07:28.655
I'm going to spend the day
pulling traps.

07:28.689 --> 07:31.416
I'll pull these, and then
I'll hop in a plane

07:31.451 --> 07:34.419
and go pull
the last of my wolf sets.

07:34.454 --> 07:35.800
Narrator: All that remains

07:35.834 --> 07:38.009
is to snap the line
for the final time.

07:40.218 --> 07:43.221
Got a mink set
right down in here.

07:43.255 --> 07:48.502
♪♪

07:48.537 --> 07:51.919
Nothing.

07:51.954 --> 07:54.404
Every season is different.

07:54.439 --> 07:56.337
You have a plan
and then you adjust.

07:56.372 --> 07:58.098
That's the way it works.

08:00.825 --> 08:02.516
And nothing.

08:02.551 --> 08:04.725
This year was a bad one.

08:04.760 --> 08:06.796
It really wasn't
a whole lot of fur,

08:06.831 --> 08:08.936
and that's truly
depressing to me.

08:08.971 --> 08:18.359
♪♪

08:18.394 --> 08:20.430
Well, it looks like
I got some action.

08:20.465 --> 08:23.157
I scored on a beaver.

08:23.192 --> 08:27.127
They get moving up these
channels in the springtime.

08:27.161 --> 08:28.853
So I just set
in this narrow spot,

08:28.887 --> 08:32.442
and she swam right into her.

08:32.477 --> 08:34.410
Narrator:
This catch is worth $30.

08:34.444 --> 08:38.759
$20 for the pelt and $10
for the caster gland.

08:38.794 --> 08:41.728
It's not a windfall,
but at this stage,

08:41.762 --> 08:45.248
every last penny helps
Marty dig out of the red.

08:45.283 --> 08:47.354
Marty:
A beaver castor gland,

08:47.388 --> 08:50.081
and they use it
to mark their territory.

08:50.115 --> 08:52.152
But beyond that,
a lot of perfume

08:52.186 --> 08:55.914
has been made
with castor as a base.

08:55.949 --> 08:57.537
Pretty cool.

08:57.571 --> 09:00.678
I've never caught a beaver here,
but that's trapping, you know?

09:00.712 --> 09:02.024
That's why it keeps me
coming back

09:02.058 --> 09:04.544
because you just never know.

09:09.238 --> 09:12.552
Narrator:
In Eastern Montana...

09:12.586 --> 09:15.589
Tom: It looks like the herd
is moving off.

09:15.624 --> 09:17.764
Narrator: ...the herd
of bison clears out

09:17.798 --> 09:19.179
after a 20-minute standoff,

09:19.213 --> 09:21.595
leaving Tom and Sean
to get to work.

09:24.736 --> 09:26.600
What a hunk of meat
that is, huh.

09:26.635 --> 09:28.429
That is something
special, buddy.

09:30.846 --> 09:35.229
I've shot lots of animals
but nothing like this.

09:35.264 --> 09:37.093
Congratulations, mister.

09:37.128 --> 09:39.544
I enjoyed that.

09:39.579 --> 09:43.237
Pulling the trigger
was the easy part.

09:43.272 --> 09:46.171
Now is when it gets tough.

09:46.206 --> 09:50.728
This is bigger than most beef
cattle that they butcher.

09:50.762 --> 09:52.626
Narrator: The large bull
will yield

09:52.661 --> 09:53.903
about 500 pounds of meat

09:53.938 --> 09:56.561
if they can break it
down quickly.

09:56.596 --> 09:59.322
At these temperatures, the meat
will begin to spoil

09:59.357 --> 10:01.186
in a little over 2 hours.

10:01.221 --> 10:02.981
Tell you what, I'm going to
hold this leg for you

10:03.016 --> 10:04.051
while we get him
started here.

10:04.086 --> 10:05.432
All right.

10:05.466 --> 10:08.124
To preserve the kill,
it's critical to first

10:08.159 --> 10:10.920
remove the intestines
and organs.

10:10.955 --> 10:12.128
Tom: When they die,

10:12.163 --> 10:14.130
the gases start
working in their intestines,

10:14.165 --> 10:15.994
and it'll sour them
if you don't get

10:16.029 --> 10:17.789
the intestines out right away.

10:17.824 --> 10:24.209
♪♪

10:24.244 --> 10:26.246
Ooh [bleep]

10:26.729 --> 10:29.732
[Bleep]

10:29.767 --> 10:32.666
Ooh.

10:32.701 --> 10:35.531
Holy [bleep]

10:35.565 --> 10:37.291
Well, it made him
lighter anyhow.

10:37.326 --> 10:38.810
I hit his belly,
I guess.

10:38.845 --> 10:41.675
-Yes.
-Yep. [Bleep]

10:41.710 --> 10:44.126
Narrator: Tom has accidently
punctured its stomach.

10:44.160 --> 10:46.887
The cut exposes the hide
and meat to bacteria

10:46.922 --> 10:48.613
that could speed decay.

10:48.648 --> 10:50.373
Sean: When you're gutting
an animal this size,

10:50.408 --> 10:51.651
it's almost impossible,

10:51.685 --> 10:54.067
unless you hang them
from some sort of equipment,

10:54.101 --> 10:57.760
to gut them without
that gut sac popping.

10:57.795 --> 11:00.936
Narrator: Now Tom and Sean
must work even faster

11:00.970 --> 11:02.351
to complete the job.

11:02.385 --> 11:03.939
Tom, I'll hold this guy
right where he is.

11:03.973 --> 11:06.976
You want to go grab
that hatchet.

11:07.011 --> 11:08.322
Okay.

11:08.357 --> 11:09.841
To reach the heart and lungs,

11:09.876 --> 11:12.533
they must cut through
a 3-inch thick sternum bone.

11:17.193 --> 11:18.367
Okay.

11:18.401 --> 11:22.543
We got rid of 300 pounds
anyhow.

11:22.578 --> 11:25.270
We got him gutted
and now we're skinning.

11:29.102 --> 11:32.450
You get it?
All right.

11:32.484 --> 11:33.727
Where you going, mister?

11:33.762 --> 11:38.628
Tom: We got a 55-square-foot
hide laid out here.

11:38.663 --> 11:39.733
That doesn't happen.

11:39.768 --> 11:43.185
One whole,
you can't beat that.

11:43.219 --> 11:45.843
Narrator: The hide will be worth
more than $1,000

11:45.877 --> 11:47.223
once it's tanned.

11:47.258 --> 11:49.709
And the meat that lies beneath
will feed their families

11:49.743 --> 11:51.676
for the next 6 months.

11:51.711 --> 11:54.299
Tom: This is a bunch of meat
in a big package.

11:54.334 --> 11:55.715
I'll tell you that.

11:55.749 --> 11:58.994
I've never harvested
anything like this before.

11:59.028 --> 12:01.859
I'll climb up in here, buddy,
and you can pass them up to me.

12:01.893 --> 12:07.036
Without Sean, I couldn't have
never done this by myself.

12:07.071 --> 12:09.659
He pulled through
for me good.

12:09.694 --> 12:12.041
Sean: Got around 550 pounds
of boneless meat,

12:12.076 --> 12:14.147
so feed the families with it.

12:14.181 --> 12:16.321
The whole hunt, all in all,
was a success,

12:16.356 --> 12:17.737
and it's something
I'll never forget.

12:17.771 --> 12:21.188
That's for sure.

12:21.223 --> 12:23.294
Tom: We did it.
We did it.

12:23.328 --> 12:25.779
Way to go.

12:25.814 --> 12:27.367
Good job.

12:27.401 --> 12:29.438
That was good, buddy,
and I appreciate you.

12:29.472 --> 12:32.234
Heard the stories about
the old buffalo hunters.

12:32.268 --> 12:35.271
And to actually get
a little bit

12:35.306 --> 12:38.550
of that experience
connects me with the past.

12:38.585 --> 12:40.587
It was all good.

12:40.621 --> 12:42.382
It was all really good.

12:42.416 --> 12:55.395
♪♪

12:55.429 --> 12:58.536
Narrator: In the shadow
of the Great Alaska Range,

12:58.570 --> 13:00.020
the meltdown is over.

13:00.055 --> 13:03.783
And in the valley, with the
growing season just weeks away,

13:03.817 --> 13:05.577
Morgan Beasley
and Margaret Stern

13:05.612 --> 13:07.752
are getting a jump-start
on their future.

13:11.445 --> 13:13.068
Let's look at what we want
to clear today.

13:13.102 --> 13:14.448
Okay.

13:14.483 --> 13:17.693
With every passing season,
Morgan gets one step closer

13:17.727 --> 13:20.765
to building a completely
sustainable homestead.

13:20.800 --> 13:23.733
As the ground softens up,
the days grow longer,

13:23.768 --> 13:26.357
it's time to start thinking
about enlarging our fields

13:26.391 --> 13:29.463
so we can get more crops
growing for us in the harvest.

13:29.498 --> 13:31.776
Narrator: Expanding the farmland
should increase its yield

13:31.811 --> 13:33.122
in the coming year.

13:33.157 --> 13:34.779
If the harvest is healthy,

13:34.814 --> 13:37.057
they'll be able to eliminate
the supply drops

13:37.092 --> 13:39.715
that they've relied on to get
them through the winters here.

13:39.749 --> 13:43.270
The whole goal is to become
more and more self-sufficient,

13:43.305 --> 13:45.617
and we're constantly
working towards that.

13:45.652 --> 13:47.136
Morgan: We've managed to get
about 4,000

13:47.171 --> 13:49.863
or 5,000 square feet
cleared last summer

13:49.898 --> 13:51.934
before planting season was over.

13:51.969 --> 13:53.867
It's probably only 1/10
of our total goal.

13:53.902 --> 13:57.388
We'd probably like to have
40,000 or 50,000 square feet.

13:57.422 --> 13:58.976
Ready to start
tearing up some timber?

13:59.010 --> 14:00.494
Yeah.

14:00.529 --> 14:02.324
Narrator: Morgan has felled
nearly an acre of spruce trees

14:02.358 --> 14:04.947
to make way for a new field.

14:04.982 --> 14:06.293
But before they can plant,

14:06.328 --> 14:08.433
they must clear
the remaining stumps

14:08.468 --> 14:10.435
and smooth over the ground.

14:10.470 --> 14:13.404
Morgan:
I mean, just in this area here,

14:13.438 --> 14:16.614
there are probably a dozen
or more stumps like this,

14:16.648 --> 14:20.238
20 of them
or something out there.

14:20.273 --> 14:24.277
Margaret: Clearing ground is
a fairly time-consuming,

14:24.311 --> 14:25.623
energy-consuming process.

14:25.657 --> 14:26.866
It takes a lot of hacking.

14:26.900 --> 14:28.350
It takes a lot
of ripping up stumps.

14:28.384 --> 14:29.558
Just a lot of work.

14:29.592 --> 14:31.698
Almost got that one up?
-Yeah. It's coming.

14:31.732 --> 14:33.424
Here it goes.
-Nice.

14:33.458 --> 14:36.358
Two of us working all day
might clear 500 square feet.

14:36.392 --> 14:43.227
So, say, 16 hours of work
to clear 500 square feet.

14:43.261 --> 14:44.849
This one, here, took
a while to get up,

14:44.884 --> 14:47.162
but I finally got it.
It's flipped over.

14:47.196 --> 14:49.129
I got to see if I can
drag it out of here.

14:49.164 --> 14:56.930
♪♪

14:56.965 --> 14:59.484
Margaret: Whoa.

15:01.762 --> 15:04.973
-What happened?
-[ Groans

15:05.007 --> 15:06.906
You okay?

15:06.940 --> 15:09.529
I just rolled on this stump
and I hurt my ankle.

15:09.563 --> 15:10.737
Did you hear a pop
or anything?

15:10.771 --> 15:11.945
Just a little one.

15:11.980 --> 15:13.050
You didn't hit your head
on anything, did you?

15:13.084 --> 15:14.672
No. I didn't.
I just went straight down.

15:14.706 --> 15:17.088
-Hold on. Hold on.
-Okay.

15:17.123 --> 15:18.952
Does it hurt?

15:18.987 --> 15:20.712
-It hurts a piece.
-Okay.

15:20.747 --> 15:23.715
I'll help you get inside
and get that foot up.

15:23.750 --> 15:25.579
-Yes.
-All right.

15:25.614 --> 15:28.824
You're very helpful today.

15:28.858 --> 15:29.998
Thanks.

15:30.032 --> 15:31.723
I hope
she's not hurt that bad,

15:31.758 --> 15:35.244
and just a sprained
or a little twisted ankle.

15:35.279 --> 15:37.143
I'm going to go get some ice
for her to ice it down

15:37.177 --> 15:40.663
and we'll see how it is
in a little bit.

15:40.698 --> 15:42.044
Sit back.

15:42.079 --> 15:43.425
I'll be out of commission
for a day or two, I think.

15:43.459 --> 15:44.805
-Just let it heal.
-Yeah.

15:44.840 --> 15:46.290
Take your time
and let it heal.

15:46.324 --> 15:47.981
Put a wrap on it later
or tomorrow,

15:48.016 --> 15:49.189
see how it feels.

15:49.224 --> 15:51.571
Okay.
-Thanks.

15:51.605 --> 15:53.262
Morgan:
We're down half the team now,

15:53.297 --> 15:55.195
so I'm going to keep
working on these stumps.

15:55.230 --> 15:57.232
You know, there's a lot
of work to do.

15:57.266 --> 15:58.958
You just got to keep at it.

15:58.992 --> 16:10.728
♪♪

16:10.762 --> 16:15.146
Narrator: In North Carolina,
in a 12-acre timber stand

16:15.181 --> 16:17.562
hardest hit by
last summer's tornado,

16:17.597 --> 16:19.530
Eustace and Preston
get to work removing

16:19.564 --> 16:21.808
the debris left in its wake.

16:21.842 --> 16:26.295
So a controlled burn
has a lot of variables,

16:26.330 --> 16:29.195
and we've got to be thinking
through the whole thing.

16:29.229 --> 16:31.921
Narrator: The mission is
to fight fire with fire

16:31.956 --> 16:34.924
and carefully direct the flames
to clear the kindling

16:34.959 --> 16:39.136
that could easily kick up an
inferno in the warm, dry summer.

16:39.170 --> 16:42.208
The challenge is to keep
the blaze under the control.

16:42.242 --> 16:44.106
-The biggest worry I have...
-Mm-hmm.

16:44.141 --> 16:45.728
...is just it jumping
out of here.

16:45.763 --> 16:47.351
We got to contain
this thing.

16:47.385 --> 16:48.662
Yeah.

16:48.697 --> 16:51.217
Narrator: To keep the flames
from spreading,

16:51.251 --> 16:54.116
Eustace and Preston
will tackle one acre at a time.

16:54.151 --> 16:56.394
They'll separate the plots
by cutting fire breaks

16:56.429 --> 16:59.328
around the perimeter in a grid.

16:59.363 --> 17:02.055
Eustace: It's really important
that we have a fire break

17:02.090 --> 17:04.816
around the edge
of our burning area

17:04.851 --> 17:06.715
by taking the fuel
off the surface

17:06.749 --> 17:08.786
so the ground
is raking it up

17:08.820 --> 17:12.617
and keeping it away
from where we want to stop fire.

17:12.652 --> 17:14.757
Just when you start seeing
that soil showing,

17:14.792 --> 17:16.173
that's where we're after.

17:16.207 --> 17:17.726
All right.

17:17.760 --> 17:22.420
When we want that fire to stop,
we want it to hit the break.

17:22.455 --> 17:25.803
We don't want it to move at all
outside of our fire break.

17:29.634 --> 17:31.774
When you can look back
across that area

17:31.809 --> 17:33.845
and see that's
a nice, safe spot,

17:33.880 --> 17:38.091
that's reassuring to know that
the fire can't really go there.

17:38.126 --> 17:41.267
-Well, that looks good.
-Yeah.

17:41.301 --> 17:42.647
Eustace: We got it cleared
all the way down

17:42.682 --> 17:43.959
to that little road.
-It does look good.

17:43.993 --> 17:46.203
Narrator: A simple-plastic
ribbon will help monitor

17:46.237 --> 17:49.378
the most dangerous
and unpredictable element,

17:49.413 --> 17:50.690
the wind.

17:50.724 --> 17:53.900
Preston: The weather is just
crucial to this burn.

17:53.934 --> 17:57.110
If it is too windy, that fire
can grow out of control

17:57.145 --> 18:00.838
and we can have some
major, serious problems.

18:00.872 --> 18:04.117
Well, let's just get
started here.

18:04.152 --> 18:06.947
Look at that.
That'll be all right.

18:06.982 --> 18:08.673
Just stay like that.

18:08.708 --> 18:14.645
♪♪

18:14.679 --> 18:15.853
Let's just start a line.

18:15.887 --> 18:17.268
I'll start this way.
You start that way.

18:17.303 --> 18:18.752
Just go a little bit?

18:18.787 --> 18:20.271
Yeah.

18:20.306 --> 18:21.824
Eustace:
So this is our first part.

18:21.859 --> 18:25.034
We want a circle of fire.

18:25.069 --> 18:28.072
So we want to draw a line
into a circle

18:28.107 --> 18:30.419
and have the fire come in
from all direction

18:30.454 --> 18:33.767
so that it puts itself out.

18:33.802 --> 18:35.942
So this is
the best-case scenario

18:35.976 --> 18:37.564
we're looking at right now.

18:37.599 --> 18:39.256
Yep.
Burning right towards itself.

18:39.290 --> 18:41.258
Isn't it?
-Yeah.

18:41.292 --> 18:44.916
I'm going to try to go
another 12 or 14 feet out here.

18:44.951 --> 18:49.921
♪♪

18:49.956 --> 18:51.854
Eustace: The drip torch makes
a big difference

18:51.889 --> 18:54.754
on being able to fight
the fire with fire

18:54.788 --> 18:59.379
because you can control and
direct and change the fire line

18:59.414 --> 19:03.245
so that we have the fire
only where we want it.

19:03.280 --> 19:11.253
♪♪

19:11.288 --> 19:14.153
That wind is heavier
than I want right now.

19:14.187 --> 19:18.226
-In the wrong direction.
-That's not good.

19:21.125 --> 19:24.128
Preston: This one tree is
catching on fire, Eustace.

19:24.163 --> 19:25.578
Oh, man.

19:25.612 --> 19:26.855
Preston: It's alarming,

19:26.889 --> 19:29.237
a big fire running
straight up into the air.

19:29.271 --> 19:33.172
And those spark's members
could fly for hundreds of yards,

19:33.206 --> 19:35.035
you know, and set
the woods on fire

19:35.070 --> 19:36.416
all around us.

19:45.977 --> 19:50.913
O0 C1Narrator: The wind is picking up
in the Blue Ridge Mountains...

19:50.948 --> 19:52.881
Eustace: This tree
is starting to catch.

19:52.915 --> 19:54.331
Preston: I see it.

19:54.365 --> 19:56.402
...threatening to turn
a controlled burn

19:56.436 --> 20:00.164
into a runaway wildfire.

20:00.199 --> 20:02.270
Can't have it getting
out of reach here.

20:04.996 --> 20:06.619
Dang. That thing took off
up that tree.

20:06.653 --> 20:07.861
Didn't it?

20:07.896 --> 20:15.352
♪♪

20:15.386 --> 20:18.182
That helped it.

20:18.217 --> 20:20.253
Narrator: The key to keeping
a blaze under control

20:20.288 --> 20:23.429
is careful vigilance over
the changing conditions.

20:23.463 --> 20:25.534
Preston: You know, once those
winds died down,

20:25.569 --> 20:27.502
we were able just
to go through and burn

20:27.536 --> 20:30.539
in a very controlled,
precise manner.

20:30.574 --> 20:33.439
Preston, I'm going to start
another circle right here.

20:33.473 --> 20:35.613
All right.

20:35.648 --> 20:37.719
Well, we got this little
triangle here left.

20:37.753 --> 20:41.550
Didn't we?
-Yeah.

20:41.585 --> 20:43.276
Eustace: Made it
to the edge, Preston.

20:43.311 --> 20:44.519
Whew.

20:44.553 --> 20:47.970
Well, didn't burn down
the whole forest, Eustace.

20:48.005 --> 20:49.248
Good job.

20:49.282 --> 20:51.974
Narrator: The first acre clears
without incident.

20:52.009 --> 20:54.460
Yeah. We got a little bit
of a waiting game now.

20:54.494 --> 20:56.013
Don't we?
-Yeah.

20:56.047 --> 20:58.084
Until the last part
is cold, cold.

20:58.118 --> 21:01.536
Once the embers die out,
they'll move on to the next acre

21:01.570 --> 21:04.953
until the entire plot is clear.

21:04.987 --> 21:08.370
I feel like we've been really
successful with this burn.

21:08.405 --> 21:10.959
There's still a whole lot
of work cut out for us here,

21:10.993 --> 21:14.445
but it's already a lot safer,

21:14.480 --> 21:16.758
and this new spring
season coming in

21:16.792 --> 21:19.312
is going to be inspiring
to move forward.

21:19.347 --> 21:21.003
We've done a good thing here.

21:21.038 --> 21:33.257
♪♪

21:33.292 --> 21:36.571
Narrator: It's first light
in Montana's Ruby Valley,

21:36.605 --> 21:41.196
where Rich Lewis is preparing
to resume a marathon lion hunt.

21:41.230 --> 21:43.681
I've been tracking this female
lion for a few days now,

21:43.716 --> 21:45.856
and this is
the closest I've gotten.

21:45.890 --> 21:48.548
Narrator: Yesterday, the dogs
caught the scent of the cat

21:48.583 --> 21:50.723
that's been stalking
a local ranch.

21:50.757 --> 21:53.898
The team tracked and cornered
the lion in a mountain cave.

21:53.933 --> 21:56.487
Rich: This cave is only about
a mile from the cattle,

21:56.522 --> 21:59.835
so I've got to get her out of
here now before it's too late.

21:59.870 --> 22:03.667
Narrator: Now Rich is readying
the team to pick up the pursuit.

22:03.701 --> 22:05.669
Get these dogs.

22:05.703 --> 22:08.465
It's only been about 12 hours
since I left the cave.

22:08.499 --> 22:10.329
Come on.
We got to get moving.

22:10.363 --> 22:13.055
Let's go. Come on.
Come on.

22:13.090 --> 22:15.368
Hopefully the lion left the cave
and she's on the run

22:15.403 --> 22:17.853
so we can get the dogs
on a fresh track,

22:17.888 --> 22:19.752
but I won't know
until I get there.

22:21.754 --> 22:23.997
Narrator: Rich stacked the
entrance to the cave with boughs

22:24.032 --> 22:26.310
and branches to leave
a visible trace

22:26.345 --> 22:30.279
of the lion's
movements overnight.

22:30.314 --> 22:31.798
She's going to have to push
some of the brush

22:31.833 --> 22:33.213
out of the front
of it to get out.

22:33.248 --> 22:35.250
So if the brush is knocked down,

22:35.284 --> 22:36.769
I'll know that
she's not in there.

22:36.803 --> 22:39.703
Let me go see if that cat
is still there.

22:43.914 --> 22:44.949
Huh.

22:44.984 --> 22:46.261
Lion tracks right here.

22:49.954 --> 22:51.646
The boughs
are knocked down.

22:51.680 --> 22:53.924
Lion definitely came out.

22:53.958 --> 22:56.340
It's definitely left this cave.

22:56.375 --> 22:58.169
So I'm going to put
the dogs on it

22:58.204 --> 23:00.275
and try to track this lion down

23:00.309 --> 23:03.451
and just to see if I can't push
her off the ranch for good.

23:03.485 --> 23:05.832
Narrator: The cave is just
1 mile from the ranch,

23:05.867 --> 23:07.938
and with calving
season under way,

23:07.972 --> 23:11.666
the herd is particularly
vulnerable to attack.

23:11.700 --> 23:15.324
I don't want to lose any cattle
if I can help it.

23:15.359 --> 23:17.499
So my main goal is really to put
a lot of pressure on her

23:17.534 --> 23:20.329
and push her clean
out of this ranch.

23:20.364 --> 23:23.988
Narrator: To keep them safe,
Rich needs to push the cat

23:24.023 --> 23:26.543
at least 10 miles
up into the hills.

23:26.577 --> 23:28.786
Rich:
They're on the track.

23:28.821 --> 23:31.720
Hopefully we can
put it up a tree.

23:31.755 --> 23:34.343
I've come this far and I
don't want to lose her now.

23:34.378 --> 23:45.941
♪♪

23:45.976 --> 23:48.599
Narrator:
In Two Rivers, Alaska,

23:48.634 --> 23:51.360
Marty's collecting his final
catches of the season

23:51.395 --> 23:54.778
and closing down the line
after an unsuccessful winter.

23:54.812 --> 23:56.055
All right.

23:56.089 --> 23:59.714
I'm going to pull the rest
of my wolf traps.

23:59.748 --> 24:02.820
Hopefully I'll pick up
a little bit more fur.

24:02.855 --> 24:04.615
Here we go.

24:04.650 --> 24:14.245
♪♪

24:32.436 --> 24:41.272
♪♪

24:41.307 --> 24:45.311
All right.
We'll see what we got.

24:45.345 --> 24:47.071
Here's the kill right here.

24:49.764 --> 24:53.008
They got it pretty cleaned up.

24:53.043 --> 24:54.941
That's a cow.

24:54.976 --> 24:57.979
There ain't much left, and it's
really starting to melt out,

24:58.013 --> 25:01.776
but I got a couple of
snares set back in there.

25:01.810 --> 25:07.298
♪♪

25:07.333 --> 25:09.093
Oh.

25:09.128 --> 25:10.336
Got one there.

25:10.370 --> 25:12.890
Looks like a nice black.

25:17.481 --> 25:20.242
All right.
Got another one.

25:20.277 --> 25:21.796
I doubled.

25:21.830 --> 25:23.142
Nice.

25:23.176 --> 25:25.869
Two wolves.

25:25.903 --> 25:27.422
Pretty cool.

25:27.456 --> 25:30.598
Narrator: Wolf pelts are
some of the most valuable furs.

25:30.632 --> 25:35.154
The last-minute catch will
bring a total of $1,000.

25:35.188 --> 25:37.639
Rich: I got some work to do
getting them out of here.

25:37.674 --> 25:40.331
Narrator:
Each weighs nearly 100 pounds.

25:44.335 --> 25:46.027
Rich:
Once I get them to the airplane,

25:46.061 --> 25:49.099
now I've got issues with how
I'm going to get them home.

25:49.133 --> 25:52.620
A little more work than marten.

25:52.654 --> 25:54.000
It's frozen solid.

25:54.035 --> 25:56.347
With their legs all stretched
out, you can imagine

25:56.382 --> 25:59.109
trying to put them
in that little airplane.

25:59.143 --> 26:00.213
There.

26:00.248 --> 26:01.905
Just barely, but I got her.

26:06.357 --> 26:08.808
All right.
I'm going to have to try

26:08.843 --> 26:11.639
and tie them on
to this stretch somehow.

26:14.331 --> 26:16.022
Try it like this.

26:16.057 --> 26:18.749
I'm just strapping it
somewhere on the plane

26:18.784 --> 26:22.615
where it won't affect
the aerodynamics too much.

26:22.650 --> 26:24.859
If I stick them on the skis
and landing gear,

26:24.893 --> 26:29.346
that's the stoutest
stuff on the plane.

26:29.380 --> 26:33.143
Get his legs...tied.

26:34.765 --> 26:37.630
The danger is if you don't
have them tied well enough

26:37.665 --> 26:39.632
and they slip,
they could get loose

26:39.667 --> 26:43.394
or get in the way
of your next landing.

26:43.429 --> 26:45.604
Once you're airborne
and something happens,

26:45.638 --> 26:48.054
it's too late
to adjust anything.

27:00.101 --> 27:01.447
Narrator: 6,000 feet up

27:01.481 --> 27:05.209
in Montana's
Tobacco Root Mountains,

27:05.244 --> 27:08.178
Rich and his dogs are hot on
the trail of a mountain lion

27:08.212 --> 27:10.111
they've been tracking for days.

27:13.114 --> 27:15.288
[ Dog barking ]

27:15.323 --> 27:17.843
Rich: Turbo.

27:20.880 --> 27:25.229
Keep going
The dog's got it treed.

27:28.129 --> 27:29.233
When a lion is treed,

27:29.268 --> 27:31.373
it can stay in the tree
for a little bit

27:31.408 --> 27:33.790
and then rest for a while,
jump out, take off again,

27:33.824 --> 27:35.515
trying to lose the dogs.

27:35.550 --> 27:37.828
[ Barking continues ]

27:41.280 --> 27:42.868
I can see a dog.

27:42.902 --> 27:44.697
See its tail?

27:44.732 --> 27:47.148
They've got it treed, I'm sure.

27:47.182 --> 27:51.393
I'm less than 100 yards
from him right now.

27:51.428 --> 27:53.016
You want to be as quiet
as possible

27:53.050 --> 27:54.880
when you go to the tree.

27:54.914 --> 27:56.675
When you make noise,
the dogs hear you

27:56.709 --> 27:59.125
and lose their attention
on what's going on,

27:59.160 --> 28:01.162
and the lion could jump down
and get away from us.

28:01.196 --> 28:05.200
[ Barking continues ]

28:05.235 --> 28:07.720
Got to be that tree.

28:07.755 --> 28:15.555
♪♪

28:15.590 --> 28:19.180
There's the cat.
The cat is in the tree.

28:19.214 --> 28:21.976
Narrator:
The dogs won't back down

28:22.010 --> 28:24.254
until Rich calls off the hunt.

28:24.288 --> 28:25.393
Rich: He's going to jump.

28:25.427 --> 28:28.465
He's going to...
Oh, here he goes.

28:28.499 --> 28:31.330
Narrator: The team keeps
their pressure on.

28:31.364 --> 28:33.677
At only 4 miles from the ranch,

28:33.712 --> 28:36.024
they need the lion
to jump back to the ground

28:36.059 --> 28:38.061
so they can resume their chase.

28:38.095 --> 28:41.202
Rich: Holy cow, the cat
is going to jump again.

28:41.236 --> 28:47.035
♪♪

28:47.070 --> 28:48.174
Good job.
Good job.

28:48.209 --> 28:49.348
Capone, good job.

28:49.382 --> 28:50.901
Yeah.
He's going to jump.

28:50.936 --> 28:55.043
He's going to...There he goes.

28:55.078 --> 28:57.114
They got him moving.

28:57.149 --> 28:58.771
She's running ahead of him
right now,

28:58.806 --> 28:59.910
but they'll catch up to her.

28:59.945 --> 29:02.326
You just never know
on a race like this.

29:02.361 --> 29:04.501
Sometimes it can be
in 15 minutes

29:04.535 --> 29:07.262
and sometimes it takes all day.

29:07.297 --> 29:08.781
It's starting to get
dark here shortly,

29:08.816 --> 29:10.714
but I'm not going to quit
until I get her off the ranch.

29:10.749 --> 29:23.623
♪♪

29:23.658 --> 29:26.040
Narrator:
In the Great Alaska Range,

29:26.074 --> 29:29.319
Morgan's cleared dozens of tree
stumps from his farm field

29:29.353 --> 29:34.600
and is down to the last three,
but he's hit a roadblock.

29:34.634 --> 29:36.119
Morgan: Worked on this thing
for a while,

29:36.153 --> 29:39.501
but that sucker has got
some gnarly tangled roots

29:39.536 --> 29:40.882
underneath of it.

29:40.917 --> 29:43.264
Narrator: Brute force
won't be enough

29:43.298 --> 29:45.024
to uproot the stubborn stump.

29:45.059 --> 29:48.856
Plan "B" is to add
the power of explosives.

29:48.890 --> 29:52.031
The way this stuff works is it's
got two different components

29:52.066 --> 29:58.451
and you mix it, it reacts
to a high impact and explodes.

30:01.006 --> 30:03.732
Narrator: The concoction
of ammonium nitrate

30:03.767 --> 30:08.427
and powdered aluminum
packs a powerful punch.

30:08.461 --> 30:10.222
Morgan: This stuff
is totally inert

30:10.256 --> 30:11.568
until you mix the two parts,

30:11.602 --> 30:14.951
and then it takes the riffle
bullet to set it off.

30:14.985 --> 30:17.712
I'm just going to set these down
at the base of the stumps,

30:17.746 --> 30:19.541
and hopefully the force
of the blast

30:19.576 --> 30:23.166
will get these stumps
lifted up out of this ground.

30:23.200 --> 30:26.376
Now I'm going to get up
on the roof of that barn

30:26.410 --> 30:30.829
and see
if I can hit those bags.

30:30.863 --> 30:33.590
As long as you're far enough
away and you're a good shot,

30:33.624 --> 30:36.075
it's pretty safe.

30:38.181 --> 30:39.527
Fire in the hole.

30:39.561 --> 30:45.844
♪♪

30:52.678 --> 30:54.611
O0 C1Narrator:
In the Great Alaska Range...

30:58.201 --> 30:59.927
Morgan: Nice.

31:03.309 --> 31:05.449
When I pulled the trigger,
instantaneously,

31:05.484 --> 31:07.900
a big explosion, a loud boom

31:07.935 --> 31:11.179
and I seen some chunks of stump
getting knocked to the side.

31:11.214 --> 31:13.492
So I'm pretty excited
that it looked like it took

31:13.526 --> 31:14.631
that stump right out

31:14.665 --> 31:17.979
and saved me hours
of backbreaking work.

31:18.014 --> 31:19.291
All right.

31:19.325 --> 31:20.913
Nice.

31:20.948 --> 31:24.779
Well, that was fun
and productive.

31:24.813 --> 31:26.574
That really shattered
that one good

31:26.608 --> 31:30.095
even though it was down
into some frozen ground.

31:30.129 --> 31:33.132
Narrator: ...one stump down,
two more to go.

31:33.167 --> 31:38.206
♪♪

31:38.241 --> 31:40.760
Morgan: I will line up with
the next one and...

31:40.795 --> 31:41.900
Woo-hoo.

31:41.934 --> 31:44.419
...the same result.

31:47.733 --> 31:50.046
Whoo. Nice.

31:50.080 --> 31:52.289
Narrator:
With the obstacles cleared,

31:52.324 --> 31:55.741
Morgan now has an additional
500 square feet of farmable land

31:55.775 --> 31:58.123
that he and Margaret
will be able to till

31:58.157 --> 31:59.952
once she's back
on her feet.

31:59.987 --> 32:04.646
See you drug yourself out
and got some potting soil.

32:04.681 --> 32:05.751
Yeah.

32:05.785 --> 32:07.063
How does your ankle feel?

32:07.097 --> 32:09.789
It hurts, but I didn't like
just sitting inside.

32:09.824 --> 32:11.032
It's such a pretty day...
-It is.

32:11.067 --> 32:12.654
...and I felt like I had
to get something done.

32:12.689 --> 32:14.277
-It is a nice day.
-Yeah.

32:14.311 --> 32:16.141
Big stumps
are out of the way.

32:16.175 --> 32:17.659
That's a good start
for the season.

32:17.694 --> 32:20.007
It is. It looks a little
different out there.

32:20.041 --> 32:22.630
Margaret: You know, it's funny
when you look around.

32:22.664 --> 32:26.151
It doesn't look like much.

32:26.185 --> 32:29.775
It's, you know, a great home.

32:29.809 --> 32:33.089
This winter was
pretty challenging,

32:33.123 --> 32:35.367
but I love living out here

32:35.401 --> 32:39.371
and I really wouldn't
trade it for anything else.

32:39.405 --> 32:41.545
Morgan: There is just a list
of potential projects

32:41.580 --> 32:43.409
that's a lifetime long
out here

32:43.444 --> 32:45.653
and, you know, we're putting
down roots very literally.

32:45.687 --> 32:48.276
And, you know, I got a lot
of expectations

32:48.311 --> 32:51.072
about living out here
and living remote.

32:51.107 --> 32:54.524
But it's just one day at a time
out here, one season at a time.

32:54.558 --> 32:57.699
I got to do everything
it takes to make it work.

32:57.734 --> 33:08.814
♪♪

33:08.848 --> 33:09.884
Narrator: 6,000 feet up

33:09.918 --> 33:13.715
in Montana's
Tobacco Root Mountains,

33:13.750 --> 33:17.409
Rich's high-altitude lion
chase is 10 miles deep,

33:17.443 --> 33:20.101
far enough from the ranch
that he can end the hunt

33:20.136 --> 33:24.209
if he can call off the dogs.

33:24.243 --> 33:27.074
Rich: They've been running
and jumping all day.

33:27.108 --> 33:28.661
I'll be happy if I can
just get my dog.

33:28.696 --> 33:31.699
Let them get more out
the snow deep.

33:31.733 --> 33:34.667
They've been
fighting it all day.

33:34.702 --> 33:37.946
The dogs are right up here.

33:37.981 --> 33:40.501
They got the cat.

33:40.535 --> 33:44.263
Narrator: If the cat jumps
again, the dogs will pursue.

33:44.298 --> 33:45.989
Rich must get them to stand down

33:46.024 --> 33:48.992
before they set out
on yet another chase.

33:49.027 --> 33:53.997
♪♪

33:54.032 --> 33:56.068
Rich:
Diamond, come here.

33:56.103 --> 33:58.622
Diamond.

34:01.384 --> 34:03.248
Good girl, Diamond.
Good girl.

34:03.282 --> 34:05.560
Come here.

34:05.595 --> 34:08.011
We got her.

34:08.046 --> 34:10.634
She's pretty tired,
as you can see.

34:10.669 --> 34:12.153
She's about 10 miles
off the ranch,

34:12.188 --> 34:16.261
so this lion can go make
a home someplace else.

34:16.295 --> 34:17.986
My dogs did a good job.

34:18.021 --> 34:19.505
I'm proud of them.

34:19.540 --> 34:21.749
I'm going to leash these dogs
up and get out of here.

34:21.783 --> 34:23.337
Try to get home back to Wilbur

34:23.371 --> 34:26.029
and take it easy
for a little bit.

34:26.064 --> 34:27.858
It's been a long couple days.

34:27.893 --> 34:37.247
♪♪

34:37.282 --> 34:40.595
Good job.
Come on.

34:40.630 --> 34:42.632
It feels good to have
the job done

34:42.666 --> 34:45.566
and have a really good chase
at the end of the season.

34:45.600 --> 34:47.188
I'm happy we didn't
lose any cattle.

34:47.223 --> 34:50.329
No livestock got damaged,
so it's been a good year.

34:50.364 --> 34:51.399
Get back in.
Come on.

34:51.434 --> 34:52.883
Come on.
Good girl.

34:55.610 --> 34:57.543
I never get tired of chasing
these predators

34:57.578 --> 34:58.820
because I love
being out here.

34:58.855 --> 35:02.100
This is what I love to do.

35:02.134 --> 35:06.345
But as you get older,
everybody knows you slow down,

35:06.380 --> 35:07.588
so I keep going.

35:07.622 --> 35:09.210
But if I die, this will be
where I want to die,

35:09.245 --> 35:10.487
out in the mountains.

35:10.522 --> 35:22.948
♪♪

35:22.982 --> 35:25.606
Narrator:
Outside Two Rivers, Alaska...

35:27.815 --> 35:30.197
...Marty caps off
his flailing season

35:30.231 --> 35:33.407
with a blockbuster catch
of two wolf pelts.

35:35.892 --> 35:38.239
But with room on the plane
for only one,

35:38.274 --> 35:42.105
he needs the other to stay
secured to his landing gear.

35:42.140 --> 35:45.039
If he slips down and gets
in the way of the skis,

35:45.073 --> 35:47.938
it's going to be
difficult to land.

36:17.761 --> 36:19.763
You're all okay.

36:19.798 --> 36:22.007
A good day.

36:22.041 --> 36:23.388
Narrator:
Marty's earnings this winter

36:23.422 --> 36:26.080
are a fraction
of his normal haul.

36:26.114 --> 36:27.944
The $1,000
he's bringing in today

36:27.978 --> 36:30.395
is enough to end
the season out of debt

36:30.429 --> 36:33.052
but not enough
to bring a profit.

36:35.227 --> 36:38.230
It's always kind of
a sad time of the year

36:38.265 --> 36:39.783
hanging up the steel.

36:39.818 --> 36:42.234
Monetarily, I've done better,

36:42.269 --> 36:46.997
but I think I've got enough
to get us through.

36:47.032 --> 36:48.067
Yeah.

36:48.102 --> 36:49.931
I hope I'll always
be able to trap.

36:49.966 --> 36:52.002
I don't know why, but ever
since I was a little kid,

36:52.037 --> 36:56.559
I knew that's the path
my life would take.

36:56.593 --> 36:57.663
It's about living.

36:57.698 --> 37:02.358
It's about enjoying life.

37:02.392 --> 37:05.878
I will trap until I cannot
trap anymore.

37:05.913 --> 37:08.433
Even if I'm old
and semi-decrepit,

37:08.467 --> 37:11.090
as long as I got a wheelchair
with thunder tires,

37:11.125 --> 37:13.092
I'm going to be able
to bang out to the river

37:13.127 --> 37:14.680
and set one mink trap.

37:14.715 --> 37:18.374
That's what I will do, for sure.

37:18.408 --> 37:19.858
All right.
That's it.

37:19.892 --> 37:22.895
Now it's just a waiting game
till next year

37:22.930 --> 37:24.966
and I can pull them
back off the wall.

37:25.001 --> 37:33.596
♪♪

37:35.287 --> 37:36.737
Narrator:
In the Blue Ridge Mountains,

37:36.771 --> 37:38.946
after spending all winter

37:38.980 --> 37:41.397
clearing dead trees
from a storm path,

37:41.431 --> 37:44.331
Eustace and Preston
have come full circle.

37:44.365 --> 37:47.748
Spring presents the opportunity
to foster new growth.

37:47.782 --> 37:50.509
So along with burning off
the final debris,

37:50.544 --> 37:53.926
they are putting down
roots for the future.

37:53.961 --> 37:56.170
Yeah. There's
a whole patch of them.

37:56.204 --> 37:57.930
Eustace: We found this little
patch of pine.

37:57.965 --> 38:01.037
It's just little baby seedlings
that's come down

38:01.071 --> 38:06.318
from the mama pine above us,
but they're so close together.

38:06.353 --> 38:08.078
They're never going
to all grow.

38:08.113 --> 38:10.391
They'll just shade
and choke each other out.

38:10.426 --> 38:12.876
So what we're going to do
is just dig

38:12.911 --> 38:14.395
a few of them from here,

38:14.430 --> 38:15.707
and we can get a pine patch

38:15.741 --> 38:19.158
started in an area
that doesn't have any pine.

38:19.193 --> 38:22.369
This little bucket of trees
will make some nice timber.

38:22.403 --> 38:25.026
Preston: I hear that.

38:25.061 --> 38:28.685
Our thought is to move them up
into a stand of mature poplars

38:28.720 --> 38:30.480
that are getting to the size

38:30.515 --> 38:32.517
and the age where we're
going to harvest them.

38:32.551 --> 38:34.657
That's going to put a lot
of sunshine onto the ground,

38:34.691 --> 38:37.349
and it'll be the perfect
opportunity for some young trees

38:37.384 --> 38:39.524
to really sprout up
and to grow.

38:39.558 --> 38:41.388
Preston: How far apart
are you wanting to go?

38:41.422 --> 38:43.804
Eustace:
Oh, just 5 or 6 feet.

38:45.564 --> 38:46.703
I guess you and I

38:46.738 --> 38:48.981
won't ever see these trees
come out, will we?

38:49.016 --> 38:51.467
It'll probably be
50, 60 years

38:51.501 --> 38:53.158
before they're big
enough to harvest.

38:53.192 --> 38:54.332
Yeah.
It's a fact.

38:54.366 --> 38:56.368
These aren't really
planted for us, Preston.

38:56.403 --> 38:59.406
These are for
the next generation

38:59.440 --> 39:01.580
and the next
generation after that.

39:01.615 --> 39:03.755
I like it.

39:03.789 --> 39:07.379
Basically, we like to think
ahead and just want to imagine

39:07.414 --> 39:10.278
and hope that a future
generation will care

39:10.313 --> 39:12.971
about what we've
provided for them.

39:13.005 --> 39:15.836
And we hope that they will
provide for the next generation

39:15.870 --> 39:17.872
just to create a continuum.

39:17.907 --> 39:23.361
♪♪

39:23.395 --> 39:25.466
That's my last one,
Eustace.

39:25.501 --> 39:27.226
That's the one
we were looking for.

39:27.261 --> 39:28.745
-Yes, sir.
-Yeah.

39:28.780 --> 39:31.334
This will make a nice
little pine patch.

39:31.369 --> 39:34.372
Yes.
It will.

39:34.406 --> 39:37.029
It feels good just
to replenish

39:37.064 --> 39:39.411
and just keep it going
forever and ever and ever.

39:39.446 --> 39:52.148
♪♪

39:52.182 --> 39:55.841
Narrator: In far Northern
Montana, Tom and Sean

39:55.876 --> 40:00.018
unload the biggest meat haul
Tom has ever made

40:00.052 --> 40:04.298
and prepare to turn the hide
into a big-ticket payday.

40:04.332 --> 40:08.716
Tom: Sean is going to help me
lace the buffalo hide

40:08.751 --> 40:12.686
that we just harvested
onto a wood frame

40:12.720 --> 40:17.311
so I can start getting
it ready to tan it.

40:17.345 --> 40:19.796
There he is.

40:19.831 --> 40:25.837
♪♪

40:25.871 --> 40:28.874
The bison hunt
worked out real good.

40:28.909 --> 40:33.120
I think we harvested
over 500 pounds of meat.

40:33.154 --> 40:36.157
So it'll feed Sean's
family and our family,

40:36.192 --> 40:41.266
and if I brain-tan the hide,
it'll sell for over $1,000.

40:41.300 --> 40:43.406
What a beautiful skin.
-Yeah.

40:43.441 --> 40:45.063
Hope that frame of yours
is big enough for this thing.

40:45.097 --> 40:47.272
I hope so, too.

40:47.306 --> 40:52.173
This is a raw buffalo hide,
50 square feet.

40:52.208 --> 40:53.830
It's a big chore,
so it's always neat

40:53.865 --> 40:56.488
to have an extra helping hand.

40:58.835 --> 41:00.803
Well, maybe next year,
we could do it again,

41:00.837 --> 41:02.598
and we'll let you
shoot that sucker.

41:02.632 --> 41:04.496
I don't know if I can live up
to that shot, man.

41:04.531 --> 41:07.188
That was pretty good.
-Yeah. Exciting.

41:07.223 --> 41:08.224
Something we'll remember

41:08.258 --> 41:09.225
for the rest of our lives,
huh, bud?

41:09.259 --> 41:10.364
That's right, man.

41:10.398 --> 41:12.884
This year has been
pretty much priceless,

41:12.918 --> 41:16.163
the times, the laughs
and the education.

41:16.197 --> 41:19.200
I feel really privileged
to be able to take

41:19.235 --> 41:20.547
some of this knowledge
away from Tom.

41:20.581 --> 41:22.618
And to be able to pass
that all along to my kids

41:22.652 --> 41:25.931
would be something that I would
hope that I could do one day.

41:25.966 --> 41:28.244
All right.

41:28.278 --> 41:30.246
That frame couldn't
have been any smaller.

41:30.280 --> 41:33.525
Sean: That's right.

41:33.560 --> 41:37.149
Tom: When Sean and I
started this season,

41:37.184 --> 41:40.118
well, I didn't know
what to really expect.

41:40.152 --> 41:42.707
I didn't know how hard
he would work.

41:42.741 --> 41:46.952
But really because of Sean, this
has been a good season for me

41:46.987 --> 41:51.474
and a success that he's
turned out on the hunt.

41:51.509 --> 41:53.407
-How does that look?
-That looks good.

41:53.441 --> 41:55.409
-Big ol' creature.
-A big ol' creature.

41:55.443 --> 41:56.583
-Good job, buddy.
-Thanks, buddy.

41:56.617 --> 41:58.274
-Yep.
-Appreciate you.

41:58.308 --> 42:00.276
Start to finish.

42:00.310 --> 42:03.969
Tom: I'm going to be here
trapping and doing what I do

42:04.004 --> 42:06.938
for as long as I could
stay here doing it.
